b'And I loved creating these songs with Aaron Dessner, Jack Antonoff, WB, and Justin Vernon. We\xe2\x80\x99ve also welcomed some new (and longtime) friends to our musical kitchen table this time around...'

b'I loved the escapism I found in these imaginary/not imaginary tales. I loved the ways you welcomed the dreamscapes and tragedies and epic tales of love lost and found into your lives. So I just kept writing them.'

b'I\xe2\x80\x99ve never done this before. In the past I\xe2\x80\x99ve always treated albums as one-off eras and moved onto planning the next one after an album was released. There was something different with folklore. In making it, I felt less like I was departing and more like I was returning.'

b'To put it plainly, we just couldn\xe2\x80\x99t stop writing songs. To try and put it more poetically, it feels like we were standing on the edge of the folklorian woods and had a choice: to turn and go back or to travel further into the forest of this music. We chose to wander deeper in.'

b'When you fight to honor racists, you show black Tennesseans and all of their allies where you stand, and you continue this cycle of hurt. You can\xe2\x80\x99t change history, but you can change this. \xf0\x9f\x99\x8f'
b'I\xe2\x80\x99m asking the Capitol Commission and the Tennessee Historical Commission to please consider the implications of how hurtful it would be to continue fighting for these monuments.'

b'We need to retroactively change the status of people who perpetuated hideous patterns of racism from \xe2\x80\x98heroes\xe2\x80\x99 to \xe2\x80\x98villains.\xe2\x80\x99 And villains don\xe2\x80\x99t deserve statues.'

b'Taking down statues isn\xe2\x80\x99t going to fix centuries of systemic oppression, violence and hatred that black people have had to endure but it might bring us one small step closer to making ALL Tennesseans and visitors to our state feel safe - not just the white ones.'

b'His statue is still standing and July 13th is \xe2\x80\x98Nathan Bedford Forrest Day.\xe2\x80\x99 Due to social pressure, the state is trying to overrule this, and Tennesseans might no longer have to stomach it. Fingers crossed.'

b'Then we get to this monstrosity. Nathan Bedford Forrest was a brutal slave trader and the first grand wizard of the Ku Klux Klan who, during the Civil War, massacred dozens of black Union soldiers in Memphis. https://t.co/n2DiEt9F3P'
b'Replacing his statue is a waste of state funds and a waste of an opportunity to do the right thing.'

b'FYI, he was a white supremacist newspaper editor who published pro-lynching editorials and incited the arson of the office of Ida B. Wells (who actually deserves a hero\xe2\x80\x99s statue for her pioneering work in journalism and civil rights).'
b'Edward Carmack\xe2\x80\x99s statue was sitting in the state Capitol until it was torn down last week in the protests. The state of Tennessee has vowed to replace it.'

b'As a Tennessean, it makes me sick that there are monuments standing in our state that celebrate racist historical figures who did evil things. Edward Carmack and Nathan Bedford Forrest were DESPICABLE figures in our state history and should be treated as such.'
